    <!-- ── Trimming keep-descriptors (INERT — trimming is currently OFF) ─────────────────────────────
         Kept as a documented starting point in case trimming is ever revisited. It is gated on
         PublishTrimmed, so today it does nothing.

         MEASURED 2026-07-20: enabling PublishTrimmed made the app CRASH ON STARTUP (0xc000027b stowed
         WinRT exception in Microsoft.UI.Xaml.dll); the untrimmed publish of the same commit launched
         fine. The rooting below was applied FIRST and did not help — the failure is inside WinUI's own
         CsWinRT marshalling layer (35 IL2081 warnings across ABI.System.Collections.Generic.*), which no
         amount of rooting our own dependencies can fix, because WindowsAppSDK is not trim-annotated.
         Trimming saved ~148 MB (574 -> 425 MB) and produced a binary that does not start.
         The publish profiles therefore set PublishTrimmed=False; see win-x64.pubxml for the full note.

         A trim pass with SuppressTrimAnalysisWarnings=false reports 52 IL20xx warnings, every one inside
         a dependency — none are fixable in our own source. The assemblies below are the ones whose
         warnings describe reflection over types we genuinely resolve at RUNTIME, so they would be the
         first things to root again:

           UnitsNet                     IL2075: UnitConverter.RegisterDefaultConversions() looks its
                                        conversion methods up via Type.GetMethod. EVERY displayed quantity
                                        in the app flows through this, so a trimmed conversion table breaks
                                        the display-units feature at runtime.
           SubZeroFramework(.Core,      IL2068: Uno.Extensions Navigation resolves View/ViewModel types by
           .GrpcContracts)              NAME (RouteResolverDefault.TypeFromPath) and the DI container then
                                        constructs them reflectively, so their public constructors and
                                        properties must survive. 45+ ViewMap/DataViewMap registrations
                                        depend on this, as does XAML x:Bind over our model types.
           Uno.Extensions.Navigation.UI Home of that resolver.
           DesktopNotifications(.Windows),  IL2045/IL2050: these register a COM activator for toast
           Microsoft.Toolkit.Uwp.Notifications  delivery. ILLink explicitly warns that COM interop
                                        correctness cannot be guaranteed after trimming. Thermal alerts
                                        are a shipped feature.

         NOTE: these are ASSEMBLY names, not package names — the package DesktopNotificationsFixed.Windows
         ships an assembly called DesktopNotifications.Windows. A name that matches no assembly makes the
         publish fail, so verify against the publish output before adding entries here. -->
    <ItemGroup Condition="'$(PublishTrimmed)' == 'true'">
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="SubZeroFramework" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="SubZeroFramework.Core" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="SubZeroFramework.GrpcContracts" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="UnitsNet" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="Uno.Extensions.Navigation.UI" />
    </ItemGroup>
    <ItemGroup Condition="'$(PublishTrimmed)' == 'true' and '$(TargetFramework)' == 'net10.0-windows10.0.26100'">
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="DesktopNotifications" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="DesktopNotifications.Windows" />
        <TrimmerRootAssembly Include="Microsoft.Toolkit.Uwp.Notifications" />
    </ItemGroup>

    <!-- Brand logos extracted from the IconifyBundle.* packs to SVG (Directory.Build.targets) and
         rasterized by Uno.Resizetizer. Items are "prefix:name"; only these are materialized as assets.
         Asset name = sanitized "prefix_name" (e.g. simple-icons:amd -> simple_icons_amd.svg). -->
    <ItemGroup>
